2 HOUSE BILL 947
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That:
3 (a) The Department of Natural Resources, in coordination with the Invasive
4 Catfish Advisory Committee, shall establish the Invasive Blue Catfish Pilot Program.
5 (b) The purpose of the Pilot Program is to curb the spread of the invasive blue
6 catfish in the Chesapeake Bay and its tributaries.
7 (c) The Pilot Program consists of:
8 (1) the For–Hire/Commercial Blue Catfish Program;
9 (2) the Mid– and Lower–Bay Blue Catfish Trotline Program; [and]
10 (3) THE BLUE CATFISH GILL NET PROGRAM; AND
11 [(3)] (4) any other program that the Department determines to be
12 effective in curbing the spread of blue catfish in the Chesapeake Bay and its tributaries.
13 (d) (1) Under the For–Hire/Commercial Blue Catfish Program, the
14 Department may:
15 (i) authorize eligible participants to run for–hire and commercial
16 fishing trips simultaneously; and
17 (ii) make any regulatory or administrative changes it believes will
18 increase the commercial harvest of blue catfish.
19 (2) (i) Under the Mid– and Lower–Bay Blue Catfish Trotline Program,
20 the Department shall authorize the use of finfish trotlines south of the William Preston
21 Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge to the maximum extent feasible to harvest blue catfish.
22 (ii) The Department may restrict the areas south of the William
23 Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge where finfish trotlines may be used to harvest blue
24 catfish based on potential bycatch, user conflicts, or other issues it considers relevant.
25 (e) In implementing the Pilot Program, the Department shall consider for the
26 harvest of blue catfish:
27 (1) authorizing the use of electrofishing;
28 (2) authorizing the use of finfish trotlines of up to 2,400 feet in length;
29 (3) eliminating any limits on the number of hooks used on a finfish trotline;
30 and

HOUSE BILL 947 3
1 (4) authorizing the use of hooks that are not corrodible.
2 (f) The Department shall:
3 (1) expand the use of practices determined to be effective under the Pilot
4 Program throughout the duration of the Pilot Program; and
5 (2) continue to implement and update the Pilot Program until the
6 termination date of this Act.
7 (g) On or before December 1, [2025] 2026, AND EACH DECEMBER 1
8 THEREAFTER, the Department shall report to the [Governor] SENATE COMMITTEE ON
9 EDUCATION, ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT and THE HOUSE ENVIRONMENT
10 AND TRANSPORTATION COMMITTEE, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
11 Government Article, [the General Assembly] on [its] THE ACTIVITIES OF THE PILOT
12 PROGRAM DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR, INCLUDING findings and
13 recommendations under the Pilot Program.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act is an emergency
15 measure, is necessary for the immediate preservation of the public health or safety, has
16 been passed by a yea and nay vote supported by three–fifths of all the members elected to
17 each of the two Houses of the General Assembly, and shall take effect from the date it is
18 enacted. It shall remain effective through June 30, [2026] 2030, and, at the end of June
19 30, [2026] 2030, this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall
20 be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
